      "text": "All LibraVox recordings are in the public domain.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 6.04,
      "end": 11.18,
      "text": "For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibraVox.org.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 11.84,
      "end": 15.8,
      "text": "Recorded by Christine Doer, the known as Assah, Florida.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 18.74,
      "end": 22.4,
      "text": "Esaups Fables, the peasant, and the apple tree.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 23.56,
      "end": 29.24,
      "text": "A peasant had an apple tree growing in his garden, which bore no fruit, but merely served",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 29.24,
      "end": 33.86,
      "text": "to provide a shelter from the heat for the sparrows and grasshoppers which sat and",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 33.86,
      "end": 34.76,
      "text": "chirped in its branches.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 36.04,
      "end": 41.64,
      "text": "Disappointed at its barrenness, he determined to cut it down, and went and fetched his",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-009",
      "start": 41.64,
      "end": 42.7,
      "text": "axe for the purpose.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-010",
      "start": 43.68,
      "end": 48.98,
      "text": "But when the sparrows and the grasshoppers saw what he was about to do, they begged him",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-011",
      "start": 48.98,
      "end": 54.44,
      "text": "to spare it, and said to him, if you destroy the apple tree, we shall have to seek shelter",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-012",
      "start": 54.44,
      "end": 59.62,
      "text": "elsewhere, and you will no longer have our merry chirping to enliven your work in the garden.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-013",
      "start": 60.54,
      "end": 66.3,
      "text": "He however refused to listen to them, and set to work with a will to cut through the trunk.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-014",
      "start": 67.32,
      "end": 73.04,
      "text": "A few strokes showed that it was hollow inside, and contained a swarm of bees and a large",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-015",
      "start": 73.04,
      "end": 73.92,
      "text": "store of honey.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-016",
      "start": 75.12,
      "end": 81.18,
      "text": "Delighted with his find, he threw down his axe, saying, the old tree is worth keeping after",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-017",
      "start": 81.18,
      "end": 81.62,
      "text": "all.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-018",
      "start": 83.14,
      "end": 86.02,
      "text": "Utility is most men's test of worth.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-019",
      "start": 87.3,
      "end": 90.38,
      "text": "End of the peasant and the apple tree.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
